Both drop in with a script tag. Both skip the bundler. They disagree about what the unit of behavior is.
Alpine.js and WakaPAC exist for the same reason: a server-rendered page needs some reactive behavior, and pulling in React plus a build pipeline to toggle a dropdown is overkill. Both are one script tag, no npm install, no compiler. The architectures diverge on a single question, and everything else — plugins, SDK integration, observability, and component communication — is a consequence of the answer.
Alpine asks: which element owns this behavior? WakaPAC asks: what message just arrived?
Element as the Unit
x-data declares state on an element; @click, @input, x-model declare what happens to it, on the elements where those things happen. The element is the unit — behavior is written and read at the point where it applies:
<div x-data="{ query: '', results: [] }">
<input x-model.debounce.400ms="query"
@input="results = await (await fetch('/search?q=' + query)).json()">
</div>Press enter or click to view image in full size

One modifier does the whole debounce. For a component this size, that’s genuinely less code than WakaPAC needs.
Message as the Unit
WakaPAC’s equivalent — a timer and two message cases — is longer for this exact component:
// query stays in sync via data-pac-bind="value:query" on the input —
// msgProc only has to react to it, not capture it
wakaPAC('#search', {
query: '',
results: [], msgProc(event) {
switch (event.message) {
case wakaPAC.MSG_INPUT:
wakaPAC.killTimer(this.pacId, this._debounce);
this._debounce = wakaPAC.setTimer(this.pacId, 400);
break;
case wakaPAC.MSG_TIMER:
this.fetchResults();
break;
}
}
});
Line count isn’t the interesting difference. Alpine handles behavior where it originates. WakaPAC handles every source of behavior through the same dispatch point — a click, a keystroke, and a timer firing all arrive as messages.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Everything in WakaPAC starts with one decision: every interaction becomes a message. Once you make that decision, many problems stop needing their own abstractions. Plugins emit messages. Components send messages. Timers generate messages. Middleware intercepts messages. The Spy panel observes messages. They’re all different ways of producing, transforming, or observing the same thing. They aren’t separate architectural ideas — they’re all consequences of that one decision.
Where It Shows Up: A Third-Party SDK
Alpine’s version of “not everything is an x- attribute" is a plain JS function feeding x-data, wired up in x-init. Wrapping a YouTube player means writing onStateChange and onReady callbacks by hand, each one setting the reactive properties Alpine will re-render from:
init() {
this.yt = new YT.Player('video-el', {
events: { onStateChange: e => this.playing = e.data === YT.PlayerState.PLAYING }
});
}Reasonable, and it works — but it’s glue written fresh for this SDK, sitting outside the attribute vocabulary.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

WakaPAC’s SDK plugin (see WakaPAC’s Execution Pipeline) doesn’t just forward YouTube’s callback — it translates YouTube’s own numeric player states into the same messages any other video source would emit:
case wakaPAC.MSG_VIDEO_PLAY:
this.playing = true;
break;case wakaPAC.MSG_VIDEO_PAUSE:
this.playing = false;
break;
It’s the same switch a click already goes through, and MSG_VIDEO_PLAY isn't YouTube-specific vocabulary — it's the same message a <video> element or a different provider's plugin would send. The plugin isn't a special mechanism bolted on for SDKs — it's the message model doing what it already does, pointed at an external event source.
Talking Between Components
Once a component already reacts to everything through messages, another component talking to it needs nothing new. A custom message is just a number in the same space as a click — defined off wakaPAC.MSG_USER, the reserved range for exactly this:
const MSG_CART_UPDATED = wakaPAC.MSG_USER + 1;
wakaPAC.sendMessage('header-badge', MSG_CART_UPDATED, this.items.length, 0);The header badge handles MSG_CART_UPDATED in the same msgProc already handling its own clicks — this.count = event.wParam, one more case. Component communication doesn't introduce a new abstraction because messages were already the abstraction.
Observability as a Consequence, Not a Feature
Because every message passes through one pipeline before reaching msgProc, that pipeline supports hooks that see everything, without any cooperation from component code. The Spy panel I wrote about in Both Sides of the Conversation shows every message any component received, in order, decoded, with zero added console.log calls — the observation point already existed before anyone needed one.
Alpine has no equivalent, for the same reason it has no central dispatch: there’s no single place events flow through, so there’s nothing for a hook to attach to. Ordinary DOM tools debug an Alpine app fine — they just don’t get that stream as a side effect of the architecture.
The One Gap That Isn’t Architectural
Alpine has years of production use behind it. WakaPAC, built by one person, doesn’t yet. That’s the honest gap — fewer years of things going wrong in production and getting fixed, not a missing capability.
When to Reach for Which
A page of independent widgets — a dropdown, a modal, a tab strip that don’t need to know about each other — is Alpine’s case, with less code and a shallower learning curve. WakaPAC’s model starts paying for itself once a component has to reconcile more than one kind of event, once components need to coordinate instead of manage themselves in isolation, or once something external — an SDK, a socket — needs to stop being a special case. The question isn’t whether your application is “simple” or “complex.” It’s whether your components spend their time reacting to independent elements, or reconciling many different event sources that all affect the same state.
WakaPAC is open source and available at wakapac.com.
Floris van den Berg is a PHP consultant and the author of WakaPAC, Canvas, and ObjectQuel — a full-stack toolset for modernizing legacy web applications.
